'''
Part A: Rabin-Karp Algorithm

1. Theory: The "Rolling Hash"
Instead of comparing strings character by character, Rabin-Karp compares numbers (Hashes).

    It calculates a mathematical "hash value" for the Pattern.

    It calculates a hash value for a "window" of the Text (of the same length as the pattern).

    If the hash values don't match, we immediately know the strings don't match. We slide the window over by one character.

    The Magic: When we slide the window, we don't recalculate the hash from scratch. We subtract the value of the character that just fell out of the window, and add the value of the new character that just entered. This O(1) calculation is called a Rolling Hash.

    Note: Sometimes two different strings can have the same hash value (a "collision"). So, if the hashes match, we still do a quick character-by-character check just to be 100% sure.
. Complexity Analysis (Rabin-Karp)

    Time Complexity: * Average/Best Case: O(n+m). The hash calculation is fast, and we only do the slow string comparison when we find a match.

        Worst Case: O(n×m). This happens if the hash function is bad and creates "collisions" at every single step, forcing us to manually compare characters every time.

    Space Complexity: O(1). We only store a few numerical variables for the hashes.

Part B: Finite Automata (State Machine)

1. Theory: The "State Transition"
A Finite Automata (FA) builds a mini "State Machine" or flowchart specifically tailored to your pattern.

    It pre-processes the pattern to create a 2D transition table.

    The rows are "States" (from 0 up to m, where m is the length of the pattern).

    The columns are every possible character in the alphabet.

    As you read the text, you move from state to state based on the table.

    If you ever reach state m, it means you successfully matched the whole pattern!

    Complexity Analysis (Finite Automata)

    Time Complexity: * Matching Time: O(n). Once the table is built, scanning the text is blazingly fast. We just look up the next state in the array. No backtracking on the text at all!

        Preprocessing Time: O(m3×∣Σ∣) for the naive building approach shown above (where Σ is the alphabet size, usually 256). (There are O(m×∣Σ∣) optimized ways to build it, but the logic is much harder to explain in a lab viva).

    Space Complexity: O(m×∣Σ∣). We need to store the entire 2D transition table in memory.

